def removeFurtherDefinitions(a_definition):
    i = a_definition.find(';')
    new_string = a_definition
    if ( i != -1 ): 
        new_string = new_string[:i]
    return new_string

    
def preProcessData(pathToFile, difficultyLevel):
    # Read the csv files and transform them to dataframes
    c1_df = pd.read_csv(pathToFile, header=None)
    
    # The original csv files have words in odd rows and definitions on even rows
    # Filter words and definitions
    definitions_c1 = (c1_df[1: :2]).copy()
    definitions_c1 = np.array(definitions_c1[0])
    
    # A definition can contain more than one definition, they are separated by ';', keep only the first one
    definitions_c1 = [ removeFurtherDefinitions(x) for x in definitions_c1]
    
    words_c1 = (c1_df[0: :2]).copy()
    words_c1 = np.array(words_c1[0])
    
    # Create a dataframe with columns for word and definition
    c1_w_d = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Word", "Definition"])
    c1_w_d["Word"] = words_c1
    c1_w_d["Definition"] = definitions_c1
    
    # Remove proper nouns (those words that start with an uppercase letter)
    # Get the index where the proper nouns are located
    proper_nouns_index = c1_w_d[[word[0].isupper() for word in c1_w_d['Word']]].index
    
    # remove the rows that pertain to the previous list of indexes
    c1_w_d.drop(proper_nouns_index , inplace=True)
    
    # Remove words that contain spaces or symbols
    non_words_index = c1_w_d[[ not word.isalpha() for word in c1_w_d['Word']]].index
    c1_w_d.drop(non_words_index , inplace=True)
    
    # Remove words that have a length less than 3 characters
    too_small_index = c1_w_d[[ len(word) <= 2 for word in c1_w_d['Word']]].index
    c1_w_d.drop(too_small_index , inplace=True)
    
    # Remove words that have a length greater than 10 characters
    too_small_index = c1_w_d[[ len(word) > 10 for word in c1_w_d['Word']]].index
    c1_w_d.drop(too_small_index , inplace=True)
    
    #Remove words which definition is too long
    too_long_def = c1_w_d[[(len(definition) > 100) for definition in c1_w_d['Definition']]].index
    c1_w_d.drop(too_long_def , inplace=True)
    
    # Add column for difficulty
    c1_w_d['Difficulty'] = difficultyLevel
    
    # shuffle the DataFrame rows (they are ordered alphabetically by default)
    c1_w_d = c1_w_d.sample(frac = 1)
    return c1_w_d

In [5]:
def mergeWordsData(dfList):
    # The parameter dfList is a list of dataframes to be merged together
    result = pd.concat(dfList, ignore_index=True)
    # Drop any word that might be repeated
    result = result.drop_duplicates(subset='Word', keep="first")
    # shuffle the DataFrame rows (they are ordered by difficulty level)
    result = result.sample(frac = 1)
    # Transform the data to a dictionary so that you can process it later in JS
    result_dict = result.to_dict('records')
    return result_dict
